itrary adoption of the Scottish name, or Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Miskell","meanings":["Irish (Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Meisceall</b> ‘descendant of <i>Meiscill</i>’, a personal name of unexplained etymology. Sometimes Anglicized as   Maxwell  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Pollok","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire and Renfrewshire): variant of   Pollock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pollock","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a place in Glasgow, probably a British Celtic name derived from <i>pull-</i>, <i>poll-</i> ‘pool’ + a diminutive suffix. The surname has been established in northeast Ulster since the 17th century.","German: ethnic name for someone from Poland.","Americanized form of Jewish   Polak  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Agnes Maxwell of Pollok was born in 1291, in Maybole, Ayrshire, Scotland, her father, John Maxwell de Pollok, was 21 and her mother, Elizabeth Lindsay, was 21. She had at least 1 son with Gilbert Kennedy. She died in 1345, in Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1291–1345":"1291–1345","1290–1385":"1290–1385","1310–1385":"1310–1385","1270–1311":"1270–1311","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1345":"1345","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1385":"1385","1270":"1270","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","Renfrewshire, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Dunure Castle, Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Maybole, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Maybole, Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1291–1345":"1291–1345","1290–1385":"1290–1385","1310–1385":"1310–1385","1270–1311":"1270–1311","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1345":"1345","1311":"1311